SIMPLE: insensible
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Insensible
<hw>In*sen"si*ble</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>insensibilis</ets>: cf. F. <ets>insensible</ets>. See <er>In-</er>
not, and <er>Sensible</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Destitute of the power of feeling or perceiving;
wanting bodily sensibility; unconscious.</def>
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Not susceptible of emotion or passion; void of
feeling; apathetic; unconcerned; indifferent; <as>as,
<ex>insensible</ex> to danger, fear, love, etc.</as>; -- often used with
<xex>of</xex> or <xex>to</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Accept an obligation without being a slave to the giver, or
<qex>insensible</qex> to his kindness.</q> <rj><qau>Sir H.
Wotton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Lost in their loves, <qex>insensible</qex> of shame.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Incapable of being perceived by the senses;
imperceptible. Hence: Progressing by imperceptible degrees; slow;
gradual; <as>as, <ex>insensible</ex> motion</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Two small and almost <qex>insensible</qex> pricks were found upon
Cleopatra's arm.</q> <rj><qau>Sir T. Browne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They fall away,⟦br⟧
And languish with <qex>insensible</qex> decay.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Not sensible or reasonable; meaningless.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If it make the indictment be <qex>insensible</qex> or uncertain,
it shall be quashed.</q> <rj><qau>Sir M. Hale.</qau></rj></p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Incapable of feeling a specific sensation or
emotion; <as>as, <ex>insensible</ex> to pity</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Imperceptible; imperceivable; dull; stupid;
torpid; numb; unfeeling; apathetic; stoical; impassive; indifferent;
unsusceptible; hard; callous.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Insensibleness</ent>⟦br⟧
